    <span class="modnum">07</span>
    <p class="kicker">Module 7 · interlude</p>
    <h1>Agents in practice</h1>
    <p class="lede">How leading practitioners actually work with the meso-level system: spec, verify, environment.</p>
    <aside class="notes">
      Bridge module: Modules 3–6 described the system; before we discuss risks, show how people who
      use it seriously say you should drive it. Spine: Andrej Karpathy (OpenAI co-founder, ex-Tesla
      AI director); woven in: Mollick (field evidence), Pocock (working method), Shankar (evals),
      Huyen (the engineering discipline). This is the macro level entering the picture: human
      judgement engaging the meso system deliberately.
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Ghosts, not animals</h2>
    <div class="cols">
      <div class="col stack-sm" style="font-size:.78em;">
        <p>Karpathy's mental model: we are not building <strong>animals</strong> (evolved drives, embodied common sense) — we are summoning <strong>ghosts</strong>: statistical simulations of human text.</p>
        <div class="signal-card" style="--card-accent:var(--ait-violet);"><h4>Jagged intelligence</h4><p>Capability spikes where training was verifiable and emphasised; it stagnates elsewhere. There is no manual.</p></div>
        <div class="signal-card" style="--card-accent:var(--ait-amber);"><h4>The car-wash test</h4><p>A model that refactors a 100,000-line codebase may advise <em>walking</em> to the car wash 50&nbsp;m away — missing that the car must come along.</p></div>
        <div class="signal-card" style="--card-accent:var(--ait-green);"><h4>Measured, not just felt</h4><p>Field experiment, 758 BCG consultants: AI raised quality <em>inside</em> the frontier and degraded it <em>outside</em> — on tasks of similar apparent difficulty.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="col vertical-captions">
        <div class="mini-card"><strong>Animals (colleagues)</strong><span>Intrinsic motivation; adapt under pressure; know what they don't know.</span></div>
        <div class="mini-card"><strong>Ghosts (agents)</strong><span>Pattern completion; indifferent to urgency; confidently blind to missing context.</span></div>
        <div class="mini-card"><strong>Consequence</strong><span>Manage by rigorous specification and verification, not by goal-and-trust delegation.</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="quote-strip">
      <blockquote>"We're not building animals. We're building ghosts or spirits."<cite>Karpathy, Dwarkesh Podcast (2025)</cite></blockquote>
      <blockquote>"They are jagged, alien tools... be suspicious of the system and figure it out empirically."<cite>Karpathy, AI Ascent (2026)</cite></blockquote>
    </div>
    <p class="sources"><strong>Sources:</strong> <a href="https://www.dwarkesh.com/p/andrej-karpathy">Dwarkesh Podcast interview (Oct 2025)</a>; <a href="https://karpathy.bearblog.dev/animals-vs-ghosts/">Karpathy, "Animals vs Ghosts" (2025)</a>; <a href="https://karpathy.bearblog.dev/sequoia-ascent-2026/">Karpathy, Sequoia AI Ascent summary (2026)</a>; <a href="https://pubsonline.informs.org/doi/10.1287/orsc.2025.21838">Dell'Acqua, McFowland, Mollick, Lifshitz-Assaf, Kellogg et al., "Navigating the Jagged Technological Frontier" (Organization Science)</a>.</p>
    <aside class="notes">
      This is the practitioner's version of our anti-anthropomorphism thread (Module 2) and the
      tropo-layer: underneath the fluent behaviour there is still a stochastic estimator. The
      car-wash example is Karpathy's own, from the Ascent fireside chat. The frontier study
      (Mollick and colleagues, with BCG) is the peer-reviewed counterpart of Karpathy's
      "jagged" intuition — same shape, measured: consultants using AI outside the frontier were
      19 points <em>less</em> likely to be correct than controls. Karpathy's metaphor, Mollick's data.
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section data-background-color="#f4f8fb">
    <h2>1 — Own the spec</h2>
    <div class="cols">
      <div class="col" style="font-size:.78em;">
        <p>The agent fills in blanks; <strong>the human owns the plan</strong>. Karpathy: work with the agent to design a detailed spec — don't delegate the goal itself.</p>
        <div class="caption-row" style="grid-template-columns:1fr;">
          <div class="mini-card"><strong>Goal, not task</strong><span>State the decision the work serves, not just the action ("report" vs "what the report must let us decide").</span></div>
          <div class="mini-card"><strong>Let it grill you</strong><span>Pocock inverts the interview: the agent interrogates <em>you</em> until the spec survives questioning — assumptions surface instead of being guessed silently.</span></div>
          <div class="mini-card"><strong>Iterate, don't waterfall</strong><span>Small scoped slices with checkpoints; one giant prompt maximises drift — and keeps the context out of the model's degraded "dumb zone".</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col" style="font-size:.78em;">
        <div class="signal-card" style="--card-accent:var(--ait-amber);"><h4>Cautionary tale: the Stripe bug</h4><p>Karpathy's agent matched payments to accounts by <em>email address</em> instead of a persistent user ID. Plausible code, wrong system design — only human judgement catches it.</p></div>
        <div class="signal-card" style="--card-accent:var(--ait-green);"><h4>Who does what</h4><p>"You are in charge of oversight and the top-level categories. The agents do much of the work underneath."</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="footnote">This deck's own repository is built with grill/spec skills — the method teaches itself.</p>
    <p class="sources"><strong>Sources:</strong> <a href="https://karpathy.bearblog.dev/sequoia-ascent-2026/">Karpathy, Sequoia AI Ascent summary (2026)</a>; <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=96jN2OCOfLs">fireside chat video</a>; <a href="https://www.aihero.dev/posts">Pocock, AI Hero</a>; <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-QFHIoCo-Ko">Pocock, "Workflow for AI Coding", AI Engineer (2026)</a>.</p>
    <aside class="notes">
      Connect back to Module 5: the spec is prose-as-program applied to a single piece of work.
      The Stripe/Google email example is verbatim from Karpathy's talk — great for researchers:
      the model's output was locally plausible and globally wrong. Pocock's "grill" flow is the
      same layer as Karpathy's spec ownership, turned into a reusable skill; his "smart/dumb zone"
      observation (reasoning degrades as the window fills) echoes Module 4's Lost-in-the-Middle.
      Cite Pocock as practice, not evidence — practitioner method, not a peer-reviewed claim.
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>2 — Build a verification loop</h2>
    <div class="cols">
      <div class="col" style="font-size:.78em;">
        <p>Karpathy's automation thesis: traditional software automates what you can <strong>specify</strong>; LLMs automate what you can <strong>verify</strong>. So make your own work verifiable.</p>
        <div class="caption-row" style="grid-template-columns:1fr;">
          <div class="mini-card"><strong>Criteria first…</strong><span>Define measurable success before generation — structure, counts, checks — not "make it readable".</span></div>
          <div class="mini-card"><strong>…but expect criteria drift</strong><span>Shankar et al.: grading real outputs <em>changes</em> your criteria — evaluation is a loop that sharpens the spec, not a one-off gate.</span></div>
          <div class="mini-card"><strong>Independent critic</strong><span>Audit output with a second model or fresh context; cross-examination exposes blind spots.</span></div>
          <div class="mini-card"><strong>External ground truth</strong><span>Tests, logs, reference documents — never the model's self-assessment alone.</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col stack-sm">
        <div class="quote-strip" style="grid-template-columns:1fr;">
          <blockquote>"Give Claude a way to verify its work. If Claude has that feedback loop, it will 2-3x the quality of the final result."<cite>Boris Cherny, creator of Claude Code (2026)</cite></blockquote>
        </div>
        <div class="takeaway" style="font-size:.72em;">Verification is where the quality comes from — the generator is cheap, the check is the craft.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="sources"><strong>Sources:</strong> <a href="https://karpathy.bearblog.dev/verifiability/">Karpathy, "Verifiability" (2025)</a>; <a href="https://karpathy.bearblog.dev/sequoia-ascent-2026/">Sequoia AI Ascent summary (2026)</a>; <a href="https://x.com/bcherny/status/2007179861115511237">Cherny on verification loops (X, 2026)</a>; <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3654777.3676450">Shankar et al., "Who Validates the Validators?" (UIST 2024)</a>.</p>
    <aside class="notes">
      The verifiability thesis also explains jaggedness (why code and maths race ahead). For
      non-code work: feed exemplar documents as ground truth for tone and structure. Cherny's 2-3x
      is a practitioner's estimate, not a controlled study — say so. Shankar's "criteria drift" is
      peer-reviewed and subtle: people think they know their criteria until they grade outputs;
      the act of verifying refines what "good" means. So the spec (slide 1) and the verifier
      (this slide) feed each other — it is one loop, not a pipeline. LLM-as-judge inherits the
      judge's flaws; that is why the human stays in the grading loop.
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section data-background-color="#f4f8fb">
    <h2>3 — Invest in the environment</h2>
    <div class="cols">
      <div class="col stack-sm" style="font-size:.76em;">
        <p>Every blank chat resets the ghost. Persistent scaffolding — the <em>around</em> stack of Modules 4–6 — is where reliability compounds. Huyen: this is now a discipline, <strong>AI engineering</strong> — building on foundation models you don't train, where evaluation carries the weight.</p>
        <div class="signal-card" style="--card-accent:var(--ait-green);"><h4>Instruction files</h4><p>Project context loaded every session (Module 5: CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md — same idea).</p></div>
        <div class="signal-card" style="--card-accent:var(--ait-cyan);"><h4>Skills that compound</h4><p>Repeated workflow → codified skill → refined on each edge case.</p></div>
        <div class="signal-card" style="--card-accent:var(--ait-violet);"><h4>Legible knowledge</h4><p>Well-organised local documents let a general model act with domain accuracy.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="col" style="font-size:.76em;">
        <p><strong>Guardrails by risk, not by politeness.</strong> Prose rules are suggestions a model can override; high-risk actions need deterministic blocks.</p>
        <div class="caption-row" style="grid-template-columns:1fr;">
          <div class="mini-card"><strong>Always do</strong><span>Low-risk routine — runs on autopilot via instructions.</span></div>
          <div class="mini-card"><strong>Ask first</strong><span>Moderate risk — mandatory confirmation before acting.</span></div>
          <div class="mini-card"><strong>Never do</strong><span>Destructive actions — hard-blocked at the tool level, outside the model's reach.</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="footnote">Karpathy's autonomy slider: you choose how long the leash is, task by task.</p>
    <p class="sources"><strong>Sources:</strong> <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LCEmiRjPEtQ">Karpathy, "Software Is Changing (Again)", YC AI Startup School (2025)</a>; <a href="https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/claude-code-best-practices">Anthropic, Claude Code best practices (2025)</a>; <a href="https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/ai-engineering/9781098166298/">Huyen, <em>AI Engineering</em> (O'Reilly, 2025)</a>.</p>
    <aside class="notes">
      The three-tier guardrail table foreshadows Module 7: prose instructions are part of the
      context, and context can be manipulated — that is exactly the injection problem. Deterministic
      blocks live outside the model, so they hold even when the context is compromised.
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Outsource thinking, not understanding</h2>
    <div class="quote-strip" style="grid-template-columns:1fr;">
      <blockquote style="font-size:1.05em;">"You can outsource your thinking, but you can't outsource your understanding."<cite>a tweet Karpathy "keeps returning to" — AI Ascent (2026)</cite></blockquote>
    </div>
    <div class="cols" style="font-size:.78em;">
      <div class="col">
        <p>Two postures for staying in the loop — Mollick's terms, from the same BCG field study:</p>
        <div class="caption-row" style="grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;">
          <div class="mini-card"><strong>Centaur</strong><span>Divide at a clear seam: human keeps judgement tasks, agent takes generation tasks; verify at the boundary.</span></div>
          <div class="mini-card"><strong>Cyborg</strong><span>Interleave at every step: draft, question, redirect — the loop runs continuously.</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="col">
        <p>Either way, someone must know <em>what is worth building, which result is suspicious, which trade-off is acceptable</em>. Mollick's rule: <strong>be the human in the loop</strong>.</p>
        <p>That someone is the macro level of our three-level picture: judgement does not automate away; it becomes the bottleneck — and the value.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="takeaway">The better the ghost, the more the human's job is understanding.</div>
    <p class="sources"><strong>Sources:</strong> <a href="https://karpathy.bearblog.dev/sequoia-ascent-2026/">Karpathy, Sequoia AI Ascent summary (2026)</a>; <a href="https://pubsonline.informs.org/doi/10.1287/orsc.2025.21838">Dell'Acqua et al. (Organization Science)</a>; Mollick, <em>Co-Intelligence</em> (Portfolio, 2024).</p>
    <aside class="notes">
      Attribution matters: Karpathy explicitly says this is a tweet he keeps citing, not his own
      coinage — model the citation hygiene we preach. Centaur/cyborg: observed working styles of
      the consultants in the jagged-frontier experiment; popularised in Mollick's Co-Intelligence,
      whose rules include "always invite AI to the table", "be the human in the loop", and "assume
      this is the worst AI you will ever use". Hand-off to Module 7: what happens when the human is
      *not* in the loop and the context is hostile.
    </aside>
  </section>

